        "#1. Explain the different types of data (qualitative and quantitative) and provide examples of each. Discuss nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio scales."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "'''-1. Qualitative Data (Categorical Data)\n",
        "Definition: Qualitative data represents characteristics or attributes that cannot be measured numerically but can be categorized or classified.\n",
        "Examples:\n",
        "Eye color (e.g., blue, green, brown)\n",
        "Types of cuisine (e.g., Italian, Chinese, Mexican)\n",
        "Gender (e.g., male, female, non-binary)\n",
        "Customer feedback (e.g., positive, neutral, negative)\n",
        "Types of Qualitative Data:\n",
        "Nominal Scale: This type of data consists of categories without any inherent order.\n",
        "Example: Hair color (black, brown, blonde, red), types of smartphones (Apple, Samsung, Google)\n",
        "Ordinal Scale: This type of data has a meaningful order or ranking but the differences between values are not measurable.\n",
        "Example: Survey responses (satisfied, neutral, dissatisfied), education levels (high school, bachelorâ€™s, masterâ€™s)\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Quantitative Data (Numerical Data)\n",
        "Definition: Quantitative data consists of numerical values that can be counted or measured.\n",
        "Examples:\n",
        "Height (e.g., 5 feet 8 inches, 170 cm)\n",
        "Weight (e.g., 70 kg)\n",
        "Age (e.g., 25 years)\n",
        "Number of students in a class (e.g., 30)\n",
        "Types of Quantitative Data:\n",
        "Interval Scale: Numerical data with a meaningful order and equal intervals, but no true zero.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example: Temperature in Celsius or Fahrenheit (0Â°C does not mean no temperature), IQ scores\n",
        "Ratio Scale: Similar to interval data, but with a true zero point, allowing for meaningful ratios.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example: Height (0 cm means no height), weight, income, time duration\n",
        "\n"
      ],
