        "#2- 2. What are the measures of central tendency, and when should you use each? Discuss the mean, median,and mode with examples and situations where each is appropriate."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2TO8tmIhx9vW"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "''' Measures of central tendency describe a dataset by identifying a central value. The three main measures are mean, median, and mode, each useful in different\n",
        "scenarios.\n",
        "\n",
        "Mean (Arithmetic Average)\n",
        "Definition:\n",
        "The mean is the sum of all values in a dataset divided by the total number of values.\n",
        "\n",
        "Formula:\n",
        "Mean\n",
        "=\n",
        "âˆ‘\n",
        "ð‘‹\n",
        "ð‘\n",
        "Mean=\n",
        "N\n",
        "âˆ‘X\n",
        "â€‹\n",
        "\n",
        "where\n",
        "ð‘‹\n",
        "X represents the individual values, and\n",
        "ð‘\n",
        "N is the total number of values.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:\n",
        "A teacher records test scores of 5 students: 80, 90, 85, 95, 100.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Mean = 80 + 90 + 85 + 95 + 100/5\n",
        "\n",
        "   =90\n",
        "The average test score is 90.\n",
        "\n",
        "When to Use the Mean:\n",
        "When data is numerical and normally distributed (no extreme outliers).\n",
        "Ideal for continuous data such as temperature, height, weight, and test scores.\n",
        "When Not to Use the Mean:\n",
        "Not suitable for skewed data (e.g., income distribution, house prices) since outliers can distort the result.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Median (Middle Value)\n",
        "Definition:\n",
        "The median is the middle value of a dataset when arranged in ascending or descending order. If thereâ€™s an even number of values, the median is the average of the two middle numbers.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:\n",
        "Consider the dataset: 20, 22, 25, 30, 35\n",
        "The median is 25 (the middle value).\n",
        "\n",
        "For an even number of values: 10, 15, 25, 30, 35, 40\n",
        "\n",
        "Median = 10 + 15 + 25 + 30 + 35 + 40\n",
        "\n",
        "Median= 25+30 / 2\n",
        "â€‹\n",
        " =27.5\n",
        "\n",
        "When to Use the Median:\n",
        "When data is skewed or contains outliers (e.g., income, property prices).\n",
        "Useful for ordinal data (e.g., ranking of customer satisfaction).\n",
        "When Not to Use the Median:\n",
        "Less informative for small datasets where each value is crucial.\n",
        "Cannot be used for nominal data (e.g., eye color).\n",
        "\n",
        "3. Mode (Most Frequent Value)\n",
        "Definition:\n",
        "The mode is the most frequently occurring value in a dataset. A dataset can be:\n",
        "\n",
        "Unimodal (one mode)\n",
        "Bimodal (two modes)\n",
        "Multimodal (more than two modes)\n",
        "No mode (if all values appear with equal frequency)\n",
        "Example:\n",
        "Dataset: 3, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 3\n",
        "Mode = 3 (since it appears the most).\n",
        "\n",
        "Another dataset: 2, 5, 5, 7, 7, 9\n",
        "Modes = 5 and 7 (bimodal dataset).\n",
        "\n",
        "When to Use the Mode:\n",
        "Best for categorical (nominal) data (e.g., most common eye color, most popular product).\n",
        "Useful when identifying the most common occurrence (e.g., most frequent customer complaint).\n",
        "When Not to Use the Mode:\n",
        "Not useful if all values are unique.\n",
        "Less informative for numerical data unless identifying frequency is the goal.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ],
