        "#3. Explain the concept of dispersion. How do variance and standard deviation measure the spread of data?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ig_8B5410jQ3"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "'''Dispersion refers to the spread or variability of a dataset. It measures how much the data values deviate from the central value (such as the mean).\n",
        " If data points are close to the mean, dispersion is low; if they are spread out, dispersion is high.\n",
        "\n",
        " Why is Dispersion Important?\n",
        "Helps understand the consistency or variability in data.\n",
        "Crucial for risk analysis (e.g., financial investments).\n",
        "Aids in comparing datasets (e.g., two companies' stock prices).\n",
        "\n",
        "Measures of Dispersion: Variance and Standard Deviation\n",
        "1. Variance\n",
        "Definition:\n",
        "Variance measures the average squared deviation from the mean. It quantifies how spread out the data points are.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Standard Deviation\n",
        "Definition:\n",
        "Standard deviation is the square root of variance, providing a more interpretable measure of dispersion.\n",
        "\n",
        "When to Use Variance:\n",
        "Useful in statistical formulas, especially in inferential statistics.\n",
        "Necessary for calculating standard deviation.\n",
        "Limitations of Variance:\n",
        "Units are squared, making interpretation difficult (e.g., if measuring height in cm, variance is in cmÂ²).\n",
        "\n",
        "Standard Deviation\n",
        "Definition:\n",
        "Standard deviation is the square root of variance, providing a more interpretable measure of dispersion.\n",
        "\n",
        "When to Use Standard Deviation:\n",
        "More practical than variance since it's in the same units as the original data.\n",
        "Used in finance (risk analysis), quality control, and scientific research.\n",
        "\n"
      ],
