        "#6. Explain the concept of skewness and its types. How does skewness affect the interpretation of data?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "RklMFbWN3VW5"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "'''Skewness measures the asymmetry of a dataset's distribution. A perfectly symmetrical dataset has zero skewness, while an asymmetrical dataset is either\n",
        "positively or negatively skewed.\n",
        "\n",
        "Types of Skewness\n",
        "Symmetrical (Zero Skewness)\n",
        "\n",
        "The left and right sides of the distribution are mirror images.\n",
        "Mean â‰ˆ Median â‰ˆ Mode\n",
        "Example: Heights of people in a population often follow a normal distribution.\n",
        "Positive Skewness (Right-Skewed)\n",
        "\n",
        "The right tail is longer, meaning a few high values pull the mean to the right.\n",
        "Mean > Median > Mode\n",
        "Example: Income distribution (a few very wealthy individuals raise the average).\n",
        "Negative Skewness (Left-Skewed)\n",
        "\n",
        "The left tail is longer, meaning a few low values pull the mean to the left.\n",
        "Mean < Median < Mode\n",
        "\n",
        "How Skewness Affects Data Interpretation\n",
        "1. Impact on Measures of Central Tendency\n",
        "In a symmetrical distribution, the mean, median, and mode are equal.\n",
        "In skewed distributions, the mean is pulled toward the tail, while the median is a better central measure.\n",
        "2. Influence on Decision-Making\n",
        "In finance, a right-skewed (positively skewed) stock return distribution suggests higher chances of extreme gains.\n",
        "In customer satisfaction surveys, a left-skewed distribution may indicate some serious dissatisfaction among a few customers.\n",
        "3. Effect on Statistical Analysis\n",
        "Many statistical tests (e.g., t-tests, ANOVA) assume normality (no skewness). If skewness is present, data transformation (e.g., logarithmic transformation) may be needed.\n",
        "\n",
        "Skewness reveals data asymmetry, affecting the choice of statistical methods and data interpretation. Positively skewed data has high outliers,\n",
        " while negatively skewed data has low outliers. Understanding skewness helps in choosing the right measures (mean vs. median) and making more informed decisions."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ck1GTHU13XdD"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
