        "''' What is a Poisson Process?\n",
        "A Poisson process models random events that occur independently over a fixed interval (time, space, or volume). It is used when events happen at a constant average rate but randomly and independently.\n",
        "\n",
        "Real-Life Example: Calls Received at a Call Center\n",
        "Suppose a customer service call center receives an average of 10 calls per hour. The number of calls follows a Poisson distribution because:\n",
        "âœ… Calls arrive randomly and independently.\n",
        "âœ… The rate (Î» = 10 calls/hour) is constant.\n",
        "âœ… Two calls cannot happen at exactly the same time.\n",
        "\n",
        "When is the Poisson Process Used?\n",
        "Traffic Flow â€“ Number of cars passing through a toll booth per minute.\n",
        "Healthcare â€“ Patients arriving at an emergency room per hour.\n",
        "Business â€“ Number of customers entering a store per day.\n",
        "Website Visits â€“ Hits on a webpage per second.\n",
        "Manufacturing â€“ Defects occurring in a production line per batch.\n"
