    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "'''A random variable is a numerical outcome of a random experiment. It assigns a number to each possible outcome of an event.\n",
        "Random variables are essential in probability and statistics because they help quantify uncertainty.\n",
        "\n",
        "Types of Random Variables\n",
        "1. Discrete Random Variable\n",
        "A discrete random variable takes countable values (finite or infinite). These values are typically whole numbers.\n",
        "\n",
        "ðŸ”¹ Key Characteristics:\n",
        "\n",
        "Takes distinct, separate values.\n",
        "Often represents counts (e.g., number of students, number of heads in a coin toss).\n",
        "Probability is assigned to each possible value.\n",
        "ðŸ”¹ Examples:\n",
        "\n",
        "Number of heads in 10 coin tosses (X=0,1,2,â€¦,10).\n",
        "Number of customers entering a store in an hour.\n",
        "Number of defective items in a batch of 100 products.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Continuous Random Variable\n",
        "A continuous random variable takes infinite values within a given range. These values are often measurements.\n",
        "\n",
        "ðŸ”¹ Key Characteristics:\n",
        "\n",
        "Can take any value within a range (decimals, fractions included).\n",
        "Often represents measurements (e.g., height, temperature, weight).\n",
        "Probability is assigned to intervals, not individual values.\n",
        "ðŸ”¹ Examples:\n",
        "\n",
        "Height of students in a class (\n",
        "ð‘‹\n",
        "X could be 150.2 cm, 170.5 cm, etc.).\n",
        "Time taken to complete a task.\n",
        "Temperature in a city on a given day.\n"
      ],
